Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/4%tsp} for the rice. When boiling, add the @Basmati rice{150%g} and cook for ~{12%minutes}. Drain in a #sieve{}, pop back in the pan, cover with a #lid{} and leave to the side until ready to serve.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} or wide saucepan on high heat. Once the oil is hot, add the @diced chicken thigh{210%g} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Stir fry the chicken until browned all over, ~{3-4%minutes}.

While the chicken cooks, halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced). Halve the @green pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips. Chop the strips into 3 pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Drain and rinse the @black beans{1%can} in a #colander{}.

Once the chicken is browned, add the pepper and onion to the pan, stir together and cook until the onion starting to soften, ~{4-6%minutes}. Add the garlic and @Caribbean style jerk{1%portion}, stir and cook for ~{1%minute}.

Pour in the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @water{50%ml}, @chicken stock powder{1} and black beans. Add half the @mango chutney{40%g} to the sauce as well. Bring to the boil and simmer until the sauce has reduced slightly, ~{5-6%minutes}. IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle. Meanwhile, zest and halve the @lime{1/2}(zested and halved).

When the curry is cooked, remove from the heat and add a squeeze of lime juice. Taste and add salt, pepper and lime juice if you feel it needs it. Fluff up the rice and serve in #bowls{} the curry on top, a dollop of remaining mango chutney, a sprinkling of lime zest and any remaining lime cut into wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!